<methodology slug="ba-planning">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ba</group>
    <domain>business-analyst</domain>
    <summary>Six-step framework for BA planning: selecting approach, building stakeholders, scheduling elicitation, specifying deliverables, establishing governance with named approvers and change processes.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>ba-planning</tag>
      <tag>stakeholder-analysis</tag>
      <tag>approach-selection</tag>
      <tag>governance</tag>
      <tag>requirements-elicitation</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Business Analysis Planning</title>
    <summary>A six-step framework that defines how BA work will be performed before requirements gathering begins: selecting plan-driven, change-driven, or hybrid approach based on context; building the stakeholder list; scheduling elicitation activities; specifying deliverables; and establishing governance (approver, change process, escalation path). The BA Approach Document is stored as a versioned Markdown+YAML file in git, refreshed on a 14-day cadence.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Ad-hoc analysis produces inconsistent coverage, missed stakeholders, and unclear sign-off authority. BABOK v3 ch. 3 treats planning as a Knowledge Area, not a preliminary step — without a named approver and a deliverable list agreed upfront, the BA effort has no contract and audit trails collapse. The 14-day staleness trigger catches plan-reality drift before it becomes a project risk.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Kicking off a multi-stakeholder initiative (>3 stakeholder groups) where elicitation, deliverables, and approval flow must be agreed before requirements work starts.</item>
        <item>Regulated programs (medical, fintech, gov, ISO 9001/SOX) where auditors expect a documented BA approach with named approvers.</item>
        <item>Hybrid plan-driven + change-driven engagements where artifacts must be explicitly declared as baselined vs. living.</item>
        <item>Spinning up a new BA capability inside a delivery team that had none previously.</item>
        <item>Seeding inputs for stakeholder-analysis, elicitation-techniques, and requirements-lifecycle.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Solo founder building an MVP — planning ceremony is overhead; use a one-page lean canvas.</item>
        <item>Pure XP/Scrum teams running on a refined backlog with a Definition of Ready that already encodes the BA approach.</item>
        <item>Initiatives shorter than ~2 weeks of effort with one stakeholder — the plan costs more than the work it organizes.</item>
        <item>When the sponsor refuses to commit a governance model in writing — without an approver the plan is shelfware.</item>
        <item>Throwaway prototypes, spikes, or research probes.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="planning-steps">
      <rule>
        <statement>Before selecting an approach, answer four questions: what is the initiative scope, what type of change (new system/process/strategy), what is the organizational culture (formal vs. informal), and what constraints exist (time, budget, resources).</statement>
        <rationale>Approach selection without context produces plan-driven defaults for agile contexts and change-driven defaults for regulated projects — both are wrong. Context drives approach, not project phase or team preference.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Apply this decision rule: if requirements clarity is high AND change frequency is low, select Plan-Driven; if clarity is low OR continuous discovery is active, select Change-Driven; otherwise select Hybrid and declare per-artifact which is baselined vs. living.</statement>
        <rationale>Plan-Driven vs. Change-Driven is not a team culture preference — it is a function of requirements uncertainty. The Hybrid case requires explicit artifact classification to prevent silent drift toward one extreme.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Plan-Driven — upfront baseline, sequential phases, extensive documentation; for stable regulatory or fixed-scope initiatives.</item>
        <item>Change-Driven — iterative, adaptive, just-enough documentation; for continuous discovery or evolving requirements.</item>
        <item>Hybrid — combination; declare each artifact as baselined (e.g., BRD v1.0) or living (e.g., stakeholder list) at plan time.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always include a hidden-stakeholders review step covering: legal, infosec, procurement, works council/union, accessibility, downstream API consumers. The most common BA planning failure is missing a stakeholder discovered during elicitation.</statement>
        <rationale>Hidden stakeholders discovered after elicitation begins trigger scope changes that invalidate the plan; finding them at planning time costs a single conversation vs. re-elicitation, re-documentation, and re-validation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Sponsors — executives providing resources and authority.</item>
        <item>Users — direct solution users (employees, customers, partners).</item>
        <item>Implementers — team building the solution (developers, architects).</item>
        <item>Regulators — compliance bodies with mandatory requirements.</item>
        <item>Support — operations, help desk, maintenance teams.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Track actual vs. planned elicitation effort in a CSV alongside the plan and recalibrate every two weeks; the first estimate is always wrong because "1 workshop" hides 4 hours of prep, 2 hours of facilitation, and 6 hours of synthesis.</statement>
        <rationale>Elicitation effort is the most consistently underestimated BA activity; without actuals tracking, every plan iteration repeats the same underestimate and projects run over.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Interviews — for deep understanding of individual stakeholder needs.</item>
        <item>Workshops — for consensus building across multiple stakeholders in one session.</item>
        <item>Surveys — for broad input from many stakeholders when scheduling is infeasible.</item>
        <item>Observation — for process understanding when stated behavior differs from actual behavior.</item>
        <item>Document Analysis — for understanding existing state from existing artifacts.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Tie every BA activity to a deliverable ID (DEL-03) and every deliverable to a requirement set; this enables traceability querying and makes the plan auditable.</statement>
        <rationale>A plan with activities but no deliverable IDs cannot answer "what did the BA produce and when?" — the question every programme audit asks first.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Name a single human approver in the BA Approach Document frontmatter (approver: name@domain) and enforce via CODEOWNERS; without a named approver the plan is unverifiable and unauditable.</statement>
        <rationale>BABOK v3 ch. 3 treats governance as mandatory, not optional; a plan without decision authority is a suggestion, and suggestions have no binding power over scope, timeline, or deliverable quality.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Who approves requirements — named role, not generic "leadership".</item>
        <item>How changes are handled — change request process with an owner.</item>
        <item>Review and sign-off cadence — specific schedule, not "as needed".</item>
        <item>Escalation path — defined chain when approval is blocked.</item>
      </list>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Governance section contains vague text ("approval by leadership") instead of named roles.</description>
        <reason>No named approver means no accountability; auditors and stakeholders cannot determine who has authority, and the BA cannot obtain binding sign-off.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="git-native-workflow">
      <rule>
        <statement>Store the BA Approach Document as Markdown with YAML frontmatter (engagement_id, approach, version, approver, last_reviewed) committed to git; diffs become the change log, git blame is the audit trail.</statement>
        <rationale>A BA plan stored only in a wiki or project management tool cannot be versioned, diffed, or audited; git provides all three for free while keeping the plan colocated with the requirements it governs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Enforce a 14-day cadence via cron + ba-plan-check.py; staleness older than 14 days is the leading indicator of plan-reality drift.</statement>
        <rationale>Plans updated only at the start of engagement and then ignored are the dominant failure mode in BA engagements; automated staleness detection triggers replanning before drift becomes a project risk.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Bake replan triggers into the plan document itself (not agent memory) so they fire deterministically: stakeholder added/removed, scope change merged, two missed elicitation sessions, or last_reviewed older than 14 days.</statement>
        <rationale>Replanning triggered by human observation misses events that happen between reviews; deterministic triggers wired to git events, stakeholder register diffs, and calendar checks fire without human attention.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Cap any agent-driven plan update to 5 changes per run and require human review on the diff; a runaway replanner rewriting half the deliverables invalidates in-flight elicitation work.</statement>
        <rationale>Bulk replanning is dangerous because it can silently invalidate stakeholder commitments and elicitation schedules that were built against the previous plan.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow-and-prompts">
      <p>Treat the BA Approach Document as a Markdown file with YAML frontmatter (engagement_id, approach, version, approver, last_reviewed) committed to git alongside the project's .aidocs/ or .product/ tree. A planning subagent ingests context (initiative brief, org chart, prior post-mortems), proposes a draft plan, and emits the document as a patch — never overwriting an approved baseline without a CR. A weekly cron-driven activity-plan agent diffs the BA Approach against the live stakeholder-analysis register and the elicitation backlog, produces the next week's BA Activity Plan, and posts it for human approval.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Require human approval at four points: plan v1.0 sign-off, every approach change (Plan-Driven / Change-Driven / Hybrid), every change request touching governance, every replan that adds or removes a stakeholder.</statement>
        <rationale>These four points are the decisions that determine what BA work happens and who is responsible for it; agent preparation is valuable, but decision authority must remain with a named human.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Two-shot BA planning prompt">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are the BA planner. Produce a BA Approach Document v0.1 using the
template in ba-planning/templates/ba-approach-document.md (sections 1-8).
Engagement context: {initiative_brief}. Org culture: {formal|informal|mixed}.
Constraints: {time_budget, stakeholder_availability, regulatory}.

Decision rules:
- If requirements clarity high AND change frequency low -> Plan-Driven.
- If clarity low OR continuous discovery active -> Change-Driven.
- Else Hybrid; declare per-artifact which is baselined vs. living.

Return strict JSON matching the template section keys.
Do not invent stakeholders not in {stakeholder_seed}.
Flag every gap as TODO(reason). No time estimates.]]></code>
        <note>Forces approach decision rules and flags gaps as TODO rather than inventing values.</note>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLM defaults to Plan-Driven for all engagements regardless of context flags.</description>
        <reason>Models anchor on whichever sample plan they last produced; always pass the engagement model and culture flags in the system prompt and validate that the output's approach matches the decision rule output for the given inputs.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent invents plausible-sounding stakeholders ("Director of UX Excellence") not present in the actual org chart.</description>
        <reason>Hallucinated stakeholders produce engagement plans with no real recipients; constrain to a stakeholder_seed list and flag additions as TODO(reason), not as entries.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent produces time estimates in the plan ("Discovery: 4 weeks").</description>
        <reason>Per repo policy, no time estimates in SDD docs; strip any time estimate from agent output and replace with complexity tier (S/M/L). Time estimates are inherently unreliable and create false expectations.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent conflates BA Planning with Project Planning, producing Gantt charts for BA activities.</description>
        <reason>BA Planning covers analysis activities only; schedule integration and resource management belong to the project-manager skill. Mixing them produces a document that satisfies neither purpose.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Keep the BA Approach Document in git as Markdown + YAML frontmatter; diffs become the change log, git blame is the audit trail, branches model proposed plan revisions.</item>
        <item>Name a single human approver in the frontmatter (approver: ruslan@faion.net) and gate updates with CODEOWNERS — no approver = no plan.</item>
        <item>Set last_reviewed and enforce a 14-day cadence via cron + ba_plan_check.py; staleness is the leading indicator of plan-reality drift.</item>
        <item>Declare per-artifact whether it is baselined or living (e.g. "stakeholder list: living, BRD: baselined v1.0") — kills the false Plan-Driven vs. Change-Driven binary.</item>
        <item>Tie every BA activity to a deliverable ID (DEL-03) and every deliverable to a requirement set; plug into requirements-traceability/ so the plan is queryable.</item>
        <item>Track actual vs. planned elicitation effort in a CSV next to the plan; recalibrate every 2 weeks. The first plan is always wrong; the second is usually fine.</item>
        <item>Stakeholder list lives in stakeholder-analysis/ and is referenced by ID, not duplicated. Single source of truth or it diverges within days.</item>
        <item>Use Mermaid Gantt embedded in the plan for the elicitation schedule; render to PNG with mmdc for executives who refuse Markdown.</item>
        <item>Bake replan triggers into the document itself ("replan if X happens") so agents can fire automatically rather than relying on a human noticing drift.</item>
        <item>For regulated contexts, sign the plan PDF (pandoc -o plan.pdf, then gpg --detach-sign) and store the signature in git; auditors accept this in lieu of paper.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="tools-and-services">
      <p>The BA Approach Document stores in git as Markdown with YAML frontmatter. Supporting tools include version control (git + git log --follow), pre-commit hooks, YAML tools (yq), GitHub/GitLab CLIs, and optional visualization tools (Graphviz, Mermaid). Integration with project management tools is optional. Jira Cloud offers REST v3 + JQL; Linear offers GraphQL API; Azure DevOps offers REST API; Notion, Confluence, Smartsheet, Aha!, StrictDoc, and Doorstop provide varying levels of agent API support. For agent workflows, git + plain text (Markdown) is simpler to version and diff than tight coupling to a project management tool.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use git as the single source of truth for the BA Approach Document. Never store it in Jira, Notion, Confluence, or project management tools that cannot version and diff like code.</statement>
        <rationale>Wiki-based plan storage loses audit trails, prevents branching for proposed revisions, and makes it impossible to answer "what changed and when?" — the leading audit question.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>git + git log --follow — Version history and audit trail of the BA Approach Document; replaces the manual revision table.</item>
        <item>pre-commit + custom hook — Block commits to ba-plan.md that drop the approver or last_reviewed field.</item>
        <item>yq — Read/update YAML frontmatter (yq -i '.last_reviewed = now' ba-plan.md) in cron jobs.</item>
        <item>gh issue / gh pr — Mirror plan deliverables and governance gates as issues so non-BA stakeholders see them in their tool.</item>
        <item>Graphviz (dot) — Render the stakeholder map and elicitation schedule from the YAML so the plan is self-documenting.</item>
        <item>Mermaid-cli (mmdc) — Render embedded Mermaid Gantt of the elicitation plan into PNG/SVG for status reports.</item>
        <item>pandoc — Convert the Markdown plan to PDF/DOCX for stakeholders who refuse Markdown.</item>
        <item>taskwarrior / todo.txt — Track BA Activity Plan items in a CLI-driven todo store agents can read/write deterministically.</item>
        <item>dateutil (Python) / gdate — Compute review-cadence triggers (last_reviewed + 14d) without timezone bugs.</item>
        <item>csvkit (csvlook, csvsql) — Aggregate stakeholder CSV exports from HRIS into the plan's stakeholder table.</item>
      </list>
      <p>Jira Cloud encodes the plan as an Epic with sub-tasks per deliverable; elicitation sessions as Calendar issues. Linear treats the plan as a Project with milestones for governance gates; agents transition states via issueUpdate. Azure DevOps uses Plan as Iteration Plan; deliverables as Work Items with custom ba_phase field. Notion offers good human-readable plans but weak typing on state fields, easy for agents to corrupt. Confluence is common in enterprise; pair with a state plugin so governance fields are not free-text. Smartsheet is heavy in PMO orgs; plan as a sheet, agents drive via row updates. StrictDoc is the best fit for agent workflows: text-first, git-native, lets the plan and the requirements share a repo. Doorstop provides Markdown + YAML, git-native, scriptable from agents.</p>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/ba-approach-document.md" purpose="BA Approach Document with YAML frontmatter (engagement_id, approach, approver, last_reviewed) and all eight sections."/>
      <template path="templates/ba-activity-plan.md" purpose="Weekly activity plan template with day-by-day activity, stakeholders, and deliverable columns."/>
      <template path="templates/ba-plan-check.py" purpose="Script: validate BA Approach Document frontmatter, check review cadence, emit JSON status."/>
    </templates>
